Someone asked me why I am getting tattoos. Easy answer, for most of my 57 years I have had people telling you need to do this or that, or you need to stand for this or that, or less of this and more of that --- I just got tired of it all. People need to take care of them self and not try to mold or shape friends in to what they want the friend to be. I like tattoos, I like dogs, I don't need a wife or partner (at 57 and never attached, I am don't think I could deal with another person in the house), and I will vote and support who ever I want to. Plus I like horror movie, I am pro-life and support the right to own guns. What is the old Ricky Nelson line: "But it's all right now, I've learned my lesson well You see, you can't please everyone, so you've got to please yourself" www.youtube.com/watch?v=PECmjB9df0w PS: I also love Taco Bell, even if my doctor doesn't.

The Jade Dragon represents the concept of our desire to reach for wisdom and understanding in this ever changing world, and more specifically, our unique focus targets the many interesting aspects of Pan Asian cultures. Produced through the natural forces of rivers and mountains, jade is considered by the Chinese to be a product of Nature produced by the interaction of the “Essence” of great mountains and rivers and the “Breath” of Heaven and Earth. The Chinese recognize nine varieties of dragons and three chief species of dragons – the lung, the li and the chiao. The lung is the considered the only authentic species. It represents the principle of heaven, the rain deity (water), adaptability, the emperor, light, activity and the maleness in the yin/yang of Chinese cosmology Japanese dragons include the ryu (originating in China - a big dragon with no wings) and tatsu (the native Japanese dragon that is smaller but with large wings). www.jadedragon.com/dragon.html en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_dragon
